# Why Window Functions?

Suppose we have this table.

| Employee | Department | Salary |
|-----------|------------|--------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|
| Bob | IT |70000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|
| David | HR |50000|

Business asks

> Show every employee together with the average salary.

Expected Output

| Employee | Salary | Company Average |
|-----------|--------:|----------------:|
| Alice |90000|67500|
| Bob |70000|67500|
| Charlie |60000|67500|
| David |50000|67500|

Can an aggregate function do this?

---

Aggregate Query

```sql
SELECT

AVG(salary)

FROM employees;
```

Result

| AVG |
|-----:|
|67500|

The individual employee rows disappear.

---

Business Requirement

```
Keep Every Row

AND

Calculate Average
```

Aggregate functions cannot do this.

Window functions can.

---

# First Window Function

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

AVG(salary)

OVER()

AS company_average

FROM employees;
```

Result

| Employee | Salary | Company Average |
|-----------|--------:|----------------:|
| Alice |90000|67500|
| Bob |70000|67500|
| Charlie |60000|67500|
| David |50000|67500|

Notice

Every employee remains visible.

This is the defining characteristic of window functions.

---

# Aggregate Functions vs Window Functions

| Aggregate Function | Window Function |
|--------------------|-----------------|
| Reduces rows | Preserves rows |
| One result per group | One result per row |
| GROUP BY | OVER() |
| Summarizes data | Annotates data |
| Cannot see neighboring rows | Can access neighboring rows |

This distinction is the foundation of the entire chapter.

---

# Mental Model

Imagine looking through a window.

```
Entire Table

↓

Window

↓

Current Row

+

Neighboring Rows

↓

Calculation

↓

Next Row

↓

Move Window
```

Instead of collapsing rows,

the window moves across the dataset.

