# Introduction

One of the biggest challenges for SQL beginners is understanding the difference between

- Aggregate Functions
- Window Functions

At first glance,

they appear very similar.

For example,

both of the following queries use `AVG()`.

Aggregate

```sql
SELECT

AVG(salary)

FROM employees;
```

Window

```sql
SELECT

AVG(salary)

OVER()

FROM employees;
```

The function is identical.

Only

```
OVER()
```

has changed.

Yet,

the results are completely different.

Understanding **why** they are different is the key to mastering Window Functions.

---

# The Fundamental Difference

Aggregate Functions

```
Many Rows

↓

One Result
```

Window Functions

```
Many Rows

↓

Many Results

(One Per Row)
```

This single idea explains almost everything.

---

# Example Dataset

| Employee | Department | Salary |
|-----------|------------|--------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|
| Bob | IT |70000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|
| David | HR |50000|

---

# Aggregate Function

Query

```sql
SELECT

AVG(salary)

FROM employees;
```

Result

| AVG |
|----:|
|67500|

Notice

```
4 Rows

↓

1 Row
```

The original rows disappear.

---

# Window Function

Query

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

AVG(salary)

OVER()

AS company_average

FROM employees;
```

Result

| Employee | Salary | Company Average |
|-----------|--------:|----------------:|
| Alice |90000|67500|
| Bob |70000|67500|
| Charlie |60000|67500|
| David |50000|67500|

Notice

```
4 Rows

↓

4 Rows
```

Every row remains.

---

# Visual Comparison

Aggregate

```
Employees

↓

AVG()

↓

67500
```

---

Window

```
Employees

↓

AVG()

OVER()

↓

Alice     67500

Bob       67500

Charlie   67500

David     67500
```

The calculation is attached to every row.

---

# Why GROUP BY Cannot Do This

Suppose management asks

> Show every employee together with their department's average salary.

Many beginners try

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

department,

AVG(salary)

FROM employees

GROUP BY department;
```

This produces an error because

```
employee_name

↓

Not Grouped

Not Aggregated
```

Even if the query were rewritten,

GROUP BY would return

| Department | Average |
|------------|--------:|
| IT |80000|
| HR |55000|

The employee rows are gone.

---

# Window Function Solution

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

department,

salary,

AVG(salary)

OVER

(

PARTITION BY department

)

AS department_average

FROM employees;
```

Result

| Employee | Department | Salary | Department Average |
|-----------|------------|--------:|-------------------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|80000|
| Bob | IT |70000|80000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|55000|
| David | HR |50000|55000|

Exactly what the business requested.

---

# Aggregate Functions Summarize

Think of aggregate functions as creating

```
Summary Tables
```

Example

```
Employees

↓

GROUP BY Department

↓

Department Report
```

---

# Window Functions Annotate

Think of window functions as adding

```
Extra Columns
```

Example

```
Employees

↓

Calculate Department Average

↓

Attach Average

↓

Return Every Employee
```

This is why they are so useful for analytics.

---

# Mental Model

Aggregate Functions

```
Take Away Detail

↓

Produce Summary
```

Window Functions

```
Keep Detail

↓

Add Insight
```

