# Visual Execution

Logical Processing

```
Read Rows

↓

Window ORDER BY

↓

Calculate Running Total

↓

Store Results

↓

Final ORDER BY

↓

Display Rows
```

The two ORDER BY clauses

operate independently.

---

# Why Is ORDER BY Inside OVER Needed?

Without it,

every row sees

the entire partition.

Example

```sql
SUM(salary)

OVER()
```

Result

| Employee | Total Salary |
|-----------|-------------:|
| Alice |270000|
| Bob |270000|
| Charlie |270000|
| David |270000|

Every employee receives

the same total.

---

With

```sql
SUM(salary)

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary
)
```

Result

| Employee | Running Total |
|-----------|--------------:|
| David |50000|
| Charlie |110000|
| Bob |180000|
| Alice |270000|

Now the total grows

row by row.

---

# Mental Model

Think of

```
ORDER BY

Inside OVER()
```

as

```
Processing Sequence
```

Think of

```
Final ORDER BY
```

as

```
Presentation Sequence
```

Processing

and

Presentation

are separate concepts.

---

# ORDER BY with PARTITION BY

Both clauses are often used together.

```sql
SUM(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)
```

Execution

```
Split Into Departments

↓

Sort Salaries

↓

Calculate Running Total

↓

Repeat For Next Department
```

Each department starts

its own running total.

---

# Think Like a Data Engineer

Suppose management asks

```
Every Sale

↓

Running Sales

Within Each Region
```

Query

```sql
SUM(sales_amount)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY region

ORDER BY sale_date
)
```

Each region

maintains

its own timeline.

---

# SQL Standard

According to the SQL standard,

```
ORDER BY

Inside OVER()
```

defines

the logical ordering

of rows

within each window.

It does

not

control

the final output.

---

# Performance Notes

Window ORDER BY often requires

```
Sorting
```

Sorting is one of the most expensive database operations.

Large window queries may require

- Memory
- Temporary Files
- External Sorts

Appropriate indexes

can sometimes reduce sorting costs,

but not in every situation.

Always verify using

```sql
EXPLAIN ANALYZE
```

---

# Best Practices

✅ Remember that window ORDER BY and final ORDER BY are different.

✅ Always think about processing order before presentation order.

✅ Use ORDER BY inside OVER when calculations depend on sequence.

✅ Keep sort columns as selective as possible.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Assuming window ORDER BY changes the displayed row order.

❌ Forgetting that running totals require ORDER BY.

❌ Confusing processing order with display order.

❌ Assuming SUM() OVER() and SUM() OVER(ORDER BY ...) are equivalent.

