# Introduction

The aggregate function

```sql
SUM()
```

calculates the total of a numeric column.

For example,

```sql
SELECT

SUM(salary)

FROM employees;
```

returns

```
One Total
```

However,

businesses often need something different.

Instead of

```
One Total
```

they need

```
Every Row

+

The Total
```

This is exactly what

```
SUM()

OVER()
```

provides.

---

# The Fundamental Rule

```
SUM()

↓

Aggregate Function

↓

One Result

------------------------

SUM()

OVER()

↓

Window Function

↓

One Result

Per Row
```

The calculation is still

```
SUM
```

Only

```
OVER()
```

changes

how SQL returns the result.

---

# Syntax

## Entire Table

```sql
SUM(column)

OVER()
```

---

## Per Partition

```sql
SUM(column)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)
```

---

## Running Total

```sql
SUM(column)

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary
)
```

---

## Running Total Per Partition

```sql
SUM(column)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)
```

These four patterns cover the majority of real-world use cases.

