# Introduction

The aggregate function

```sql
COUNT()
```

counts rows or values.

For example,

```sql
SELECT

COUNT(*)

FROM employees;
```

returns

```
One Number
```

However,

many analytical reports require

```
Every Row

+

Count Information
```

Examples include

- Every employee with department employee count
- Every order with customer order count
- Every product with category product count
- Every student with class strength

This is where

```sql
COUNT()

OVER()
```

becomes useful.

---

# The Fundamental Rule

```
COUNT()

↓

Aggregate Function

↓

One Result

----------------------

COUNT()

OVER()

↓

Window Function

↓

One Result

Per Row
```

The calculation remains

```
COUNT
```

Only

```
OVER()
```

changes

how SQL returns the result.

---

# Syntax

## Count All Rows

```sql
COUNT(*)

OVER()
```

---

## Count Rows Per Partition

```sql
COUNT(*)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)
```

---

## Running Count

```sql
COUNT(*)

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary
)
```

---

## Running Count Per Partition

```sql
COUNT(*)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)
```

---

# Example Dataset

| Employee | Department | Salary |
|-----------|------------|--------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|
| Bob | IT |70000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|
| David | HR |50000|

---

# Example 1
# Company Employee Count

