# ==========================================================

# Introduction

You have now learned the four ranking functions available in PostgreSQL.

- ROW_NUMBER()
- RANK()
- DENSE_RANK()
- NTILE()

Although their syntax looks similar,

they solve different business problems.

One of the most common SQL interview questions is

> Which ranking function would you use, and why?

The correct answer depends entirely on the business requirement.

This section provides a practical framework for choosing the right function.

---

# The Four Ranking Functions

| Function | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| ROW_NUMBER() | Assign a unique sequential number to every row |
| RANK() | Assign the same rank to tied values and leave gaps |
| DENSE_RANK() | Assign the same rank to tied values without gaps |
| NTILE() | Divide rows into approximately equal-sized groups |

Think of these as four different tools.

Each tool solves a different problem.

---

# Decision Tree

```
Need A Unique Number?

↓

YES

↓

ROW_NUMBER()

=============================

NO

↓

Should Equal Values

Share The Same Rank?

↓

YES

↓

Should Ranks Have Gaps?

↓

YES

↓

RANK()

-----------------------------

NO

↓

DENSE_RANK()

=============================

Need Groups Instead Of Ranks?

↓

NTILE()
```

Memorizing this decision tree is enough to answer many interview questions.

---

# Comparison Table

| Feature | ROW_NUMBER() | RANK() | DENSE_RANK() | NTILE() |
|----------|--------------|---------|--------------|----------|
| Unique Number Per Row | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| Equal Values Share Number | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | Depends on group boundaries |
| Gaps After Ties | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | N/A |
| Divides Into Groups | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Uses ORDER BY | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Supports PARTITION BY | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

---

# One Dataset

Consider

| Employee | Salary |
|-----------|--------:|
| Alice |90000|
| Bob |70000|
| Charlie |70000|
| David |50000|

---

# ROW_NUMBER()

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

ROW_NUMBER()

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary DESC
)

AS row_num

FROM employees;
```

Result

| Salary | Result |
|--------:|-------:|
|90000|1|
|70000|2|
|70000|3|
|50000|4|

Every row

receives

a unique number.

---

# RANK()

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

RANK()

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary DESC
)

AS salary_rank

FROM employees;
```

Result

