# Section 35.24
# Named Windows (WINDOW Clause)
# ==========================================================

# Introduction

As window queries become larger,

it is common

to use

multiple window functions.

Example

```sql
SELECT

SUM(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
),

AVG(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
),

ROW_NUMBER()

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)

FROM employees;
```

Notice

the same

window definition

is repeated

three times.

This makes

queries

longer,

harder to read,

and more difficult

to maintain.

The

```
WINDOW
```

clause

solves this problem.

---

# What Is a Named Window?

A named window

is simply

a reusable

window definition.

Instead of writing

```
OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)
```

multiple times,

we define it once

and reuse it.

---

# Syntax

```sql
SELECT

...

OVER window_name

FROM table

WINDOW

window_name AS
(
PARTITION BY ...

ORDER BY ...
);
```

The

```
WINDOW
```

clause

appears

after

```
FROM

WHERE

GROUP BY

HAVING
```

and before

the final

```
ORDER BY
```

---

# Without Named Windows

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

SUM(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
),

AVG(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
),

COUNT(*)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
)

FROM employees;
```

Notice

the repetition.

---

# With Named Windows

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

SUM(salary)

OVER dept_window,

AVG(salary)

OVER dept_window,

COUNT(*)

OVER dept_window

FROM employees

WINDOW

dept_window AS
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
);
```

Much shorter.

Much easier

to maintain.

---

# Execution Diagram

```
Window Definition

↓

dept_window

↓

PARTITION BY department

↓

ORDER BY salary

======================

SUM()

↓

Uses

dept_window

----------------------

AVG()

↓

Uses

dept_window

----------------------

COUNT()

↓

Uses

dept_window
```

One definition.

Multiple uses.

---

# Example Dataset

| Employee | Department | Salary |
|-----------|------------|--------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|
| Bob | IT |70000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|
| David | HR |50000|

---

# Example 1
# Running Total and Average

Query

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

department,

salary,

SUM(salary)

OVER dept_window

AS running_total,

AVG(salary)

OVER dept_window

AS running_average

FROM employees

WINDOW

dept_window AS
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary
);
```

Both functions

use

the same

named window.

---

# Why Use Named Windows?

Benefits

```
Less Code

↓

Better Readability

↓

Easier Maintenance

↓

Lower Chance

Of Errors
```

If

the partition

or

ordering

changes,

it only needs

to be updated

once.

---

# Multiple Named Windows

A query

may define

more than one

named window.

Example

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

ROW_NUMBER()

OVER salary_window,

COUNT(*)

OVER department_window

FROM employees

WINDOW

salary_window AS
(
ORDER BY salary DESC
),

department_window AS
(
PARTITION BY department
);
```

Each window

serves

a different purpose.

---

# Inheriting Window Definitions

Named windows

can be

based on

other named windows.

Example

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

salary,

SUM(salary)

OVER salary_window

FROM employees

WINDOW

base_window AS
(
PARTITION BY department
),

salary_window AS
(
base_window

ORDER BY salary
);
```

Here,

`salary_window`

inherits

the partitioning

from

`base_window`

and adds

an

```
ORDER BY
```

This reduces

duplication

even further.

---

# Business Example

HR Dashboard

Business asks

```
Running Total

↓

Department Average

↓

Employee Rank
```

All three

use

the same

department

window.

Named windows

avoid

repeating

the same

definition

multiple times.

---

# Think Like a Data Engineer

Suppose

an ETL job

contains

```
12

Window Functions
```

Without

named windows,

the same

```
PARTITION BY

customer_id

ORDER BY

transaction_date
```

may be written

twelve times.

One typo

creates

incorrect results.

Using

a named window

reduces

that risk.

---

# Named Windows and Performance

A named window

does

not

automatically

make

a query faster.

Its primary benefit

is

```
Readability

Maintainability
```

However,

because multiple functions

share

the same

window specification,

the PostgreSQL planner

can often recognize

that they use

the same window definition

and reuse work where appropriate.

The performance gain

comes from

sharing

the window definition,

not

from

the keyword

itself.

---

# Logical Execution

Conceptually

```
Define Window

↓

Assign Name

↓

Apply Window

To Each Function

↓

Execute Window Functions

↓

Return Results
```

---

# Best Practices

✅ Use meaningful window names such as

```
department_window

salary_window

customer_window
```

instead of

```
w1

w2
```

---

✅ Reuse

common

window definitions.

---

✅ Group

related

window functions

together.

---

✅ Keep

window definitions

simple

and descriptive.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Assuming

named windows

change

query results.

They only

reuse

the window definition.

---

❌ Giving

unclear names

such as

```
w1

abc

temp
```

---

❌ Creating

many

nearly identical

named windows

instead of

sharing

a common base.

---

❌ Forgetting

that each

window function

can still specify

its own frame

when required.

