# Combining Multiple Window Functions
# ==========================================================

# Introduction

Until now,

we have studied

each window function

individually.

In real-world applications,

however,

queries rarely use

only one

window function.

A single business report

may require

```
Running Total

↓

Running Average

↓

Employee Rank

↓

Previous Salary

↓

Department Total

↓

Highest Salary
```

All in

one query.

Fortunately,

PostgreSQL

allows

multiple

window functions

to be combined

within the same

SELECT statement.

---

# Why Combine Window Functions?

Businesses often ask questions like

```
Employee

↓

Department Rank

↓

Company Rank

↓

Department Average

↓

Previous Salary

↓

Running Total
```

Instead of

writing

multiple queries,

PostgreSQL

can calculate

everything

at once.

---

# Example Dataset

| Employee | Department | Salary |
|-----------|------------|--------:|
| Alice | IT |90000|
| Bob | IT |70000|
| Charlie | HR |60000|
| David | HR |50000|

---

# Example 1
# Aggregate + Ranking

Query

```sql
SELECT

employee_name,

department,

salary,

SUM(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)

AS department_total,

AVG(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)

AS department_average,

RANK()

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary DESC
)

AS company_rank

FROM employees;
```

---

Result

| Employee | Dept Total | Dept Avg | Company Rank |
|-----------|-----------:|---------:|-------------:|
| Alice |160000|80000|1|
| Bob |160000|80000|2|
| Charlie |110000|55000|3|
| David |110000|55000|4|

One query

calculates

aggregates

and

ranking

together.

---

