---

# Mixing Window Definitions

Some functions

share

the same

window definition.

Others

need

different ones.

Example

```sql
AVG(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)
```

and

```sql
SUM(salary)

OVER
(
PARTITION BY department
)
```

share

the same partition.

---

While

```sql
RANK()

OVER
(
ORDER BY salary DESC
)
```

requires

a different

window definition.

---

# Using Named Windows

When

multiple functions

share

the same

window definition,

use

named windows.

Example

```sql
SELECT

SUM(salary)

OVER dept_window,

AVG(salary)

OVER dept_window,

ROW_NUMBER()

OVER dept_window

FROM employees

WINDOW

dept_window AS
(
PARTITION BY department

ORDER BY salary DESC
);
```

Cleaner

and

easier

to maintain.

---

# Think Like a Data Engineer

Suppose

an ETL pipeline

builds

a reporting table.

Business asks for

- Running revenue
- Customer rank
- Previous order
- Department total
- Daily growth

Instead of

five

separate queries,

a single

window-function query

can populate

all columns

during one pass

over the data.

---

# Performance Considerations

Combining

many

window functions

does not

necessarily mean

multiple sorts.

If

functions

share

the same

```
PARTITION BY

ORDER BY
```

PostgreSQL

can often

reuse

the same

window processing.

Different

window definitions

may require

additional

sorting

or

WindowAgg

operations.

Always inspect

```sql
EXPLAIN ANALYZE
```

for production queries.

---

# Best Practices

✅ Combine related window functions in one query when it improves clarity.

✅ Reuse the same window definition whenever possible.

✅ Use named windows for repeated specifications.

✅ Group related calculations together.

✅ Test performance with realistic data volumes.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Writing multiple queries when one window query is sufficient.

❌ Repeating identical window definitions instead of using named windows.

❌ Mixing unrelated window definitions without understanding the performance impact.

❌ Forgetting that different `ORDER BY` clauses may require additional sorting.

